{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487345"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:06:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"326"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/326"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.49,0.38,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64115"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/326"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"326"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49546"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3461"},{"type":"tags","id":"4493"},{"type":"tags","id":"9572"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64115"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents with a six-day history of severe right upper quadrant pain and fever. Three weeks earlier she has been hospitalised with a myocardial infarction and is now on dual antiplatelet therapy. Her medical history also includes chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, for which she uses a long-acting bronchodilator. She is a reformed smoker and drinks two glasses of wine a day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she looks unwell, with a temperature of 38.7\u00baC, blood pressure 110/70mmHg and pulse rate 90/min. There is tenderness and guarding in the right upper quadrant. Ultrasound examination shows a thick-walled gallbladder with a stone impacted at the neck with features of severe inflammation around the porta hepatis. She is treated with intravenous fluids and antibiotics. Three days later there has been no improvement and the area of abdominal tenderness has increased.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue current plan of management","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy","Percutaneous cholecystostomy","Endoscopic sphincterotomy","Open cholecystectomy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ideal plan of management for a patient with acute cholecystitis is early cholecystectomy within seven days of onset of symptoms. This is on the assumption that the patient is fit for a surgical procedure. In this case, the patient has important co-morbidities of chronic obstructive airways disease and a recent myocardial infarction. These would put her at high risk. In addition, her symptoms started six days prior to admission, which would add to the technical challenges even if she was fit for surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe is not improving despite aggressive medical treatment. Most patients with acute cholecystitis will respond to medical measures of antibiotics, gut rest and intravenous fluid - however, a small percentage will deteriorate. In these cases surgical intervention is usually the most appropriate next option. With the recent myocardial infarction, the risk of further infarction after surgery is considerably increased for any procedure performed within the first six months. Without decompression of the gallbladder, she will continue to deteriorate and a \u003Cstrong\u003Epercutaneous cholecystostomy\u003C/strong\u003E should now be considered. In this particular case, the patient might have been considered for percutaneous cholecystostomy as soon as she presented, rather than waiting to see how she responded to medical management. A definitive procedure (cholecystectomy) can be considered later.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A percutaneous cholecystostomy is a safe procedure for patients with acute unresolving cholecystitis, who are not fit for surgery."],"references":["Halpin V. Acute cholecystitis. Clinical Evidence 2014;08:411. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25144428/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"326"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49546"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T23:01:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T23:01:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"326"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64115"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"73","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/a